If you visit Teotitlan del Valle to attend the fair for woven goods and textiles on the last weekend of September, when most of the men have left home for Mexico City and members of the National Fibrous Design Demostrations School of Oaxaca participate in national workshops in Tyre, you will also see the carpentry competition as well as an indigenous corn competition, on the edge of the river in front of Santa Monica.

This is marvalous event to observe such compelling culture concentrated and to taste the unique Oaxacan food.

The long river bending down from the blue high mountains curving down to Jalatlaco is where farmers and Mesmere traders traveled to get the best tradings deals.

Every October and other months of the year, Teotitlan locals organize Ana Sonora for the feast day of the Virgin of the Rosary coinciding with the last harvest season when the months of drying and washing, starching, ironing, planning, then doing sewing, weaving, weaving, weaving, popping, roasting, frying, sauces, whipping the silk yarns takes place.
